class Solution:
    def asteroidsDestroyed(self, mass: int, asteroids: List[int]) -> bool:
        asteroids.sort()
        cur = mass
        for a in asteroids:
            if cur < a:
                return False
            cur += a
        return True

"""
Approach & Reasoning:
To destroy all asteroids we must always collide with an asteroid that is <= our current mass (otherwise the planet is destroyed). To maximize the chance of success we should always tackle the smallest remaining asteroid first — this grows our mass as quickly as possible before we encounter larger asteroids.

Therefore:
1. Sort the asteroid array in non-decreasing order (O(n log n)).
2. Iterate through the sorted list:
   - If the current asteroid mass > our current planet mass, it is impossible to destroy it (return false).
   - Otherwise destroy it and add its mass to the planet.
3. If we successfully process every asteroid, return true.

Because we always choose the smallest possible next asteroid, any feasible ordering must also be able to handle the asteroids in this sorted sequence (otherwise a larger asteroid would have been encountered earlier with insufficient mass). The algorithm runs in O(n log n) time due to sorting and O(n) additional work for the linear scan.

Time Complexity: O(n log n)
Space Complexity: O(1) (sorting is performed in-place)
"""
